</category><category>small business social</category><category>social media for local businesses</category><category>social media for small business</category><category>social media strategies</category><category>social media strategies for small business</category><category>starting with social media</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">jmacofearth</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 26 Jul 2011 11:09:39 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://uber.la/?p=22706</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-Shot-2011-07-26-at-1.08.29-PM.png"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-22709" title="Social Media for Small Business" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-Shot-2011-07-26-at-1.08.29-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2011 07 26 at 1.08.29 PM Social Media Strategies for Small Business" width="108" height="110" /></a>It&#039;s the question I am asked most often.</p>
<p><strong>&#034;Social media is great and all, but can it move the needle for me in my small business?&#034;</strong></p>
<p>Most of the great stories of social media success involve large brands and corporations like Dell, Best Buy, and Pepsi. While the case studies are interesting it is hard to pull salient information to help small businesses engage in successful social media marketing.</p>
<p>After 7+ years working in the corporate social media space I am going to be turning my focus and consulting practice towards helping smaller, local businesses get up and running with success-driven social media programs.</p>
<p>I&#039;ve been writing about Twitter, LinkedIN, Facebook and social media strategies since 2009, and while I&#039;ve learned a lot in that process, my focus has been more on corporate social media success. I am creating a <a title="Social Media Strategies for Small Business" href="http://uber.la/social-media-strategies-for-business/">Social Media Strategies for Small Business</a> page that will organize and capture relevant information that should help you help yourselves.</p>
<p>That&#039;s my goal. I am here to help, as a consultant, but much of what you need to do, only you can do. I can help guide you with content strategies, help you structure your web page/blog/facebook page, all those details, but the real social part can only be added by you and your employees and ultimately your customers.</p>
<p>My primary refrain in social media, <strong>&#034;It&#039;s not about what you say about your business, it&#039;s what others are saying about your business.&#034;</strong></p>
<p>That&#039;s social media. Uber.la is great resource for tools and strategies for getting the conversation started and figuring out how to turn that &#034;social&#034; activity into business.</p>
<p>I hope you enjoy the journey. And I&#039;m <a title="How to work with John McElhenney for your social media success" href="http://uber.la/work-with-me/">here to help</a> if you need me.</p>
