</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Uberla/~4/OoaYbXKqmxQ" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>What was I thinking? I got what looked like a legitimate message about a new Twitter tool. And something about stalking. Perhaps that should've been the clue. But I went along for a looksee. And in the process opened my account up to a scam of some sort. The StalkTrak, LTwitteri(d0t)com, Twitter Hack.</description><wfw:commentRss xmlns:wfw="http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/">http://uber.la/2011/07/twitter-hack/feed/</wfw:commentRss><slash:comments xmlns:slash="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/">5</slash:comments><feedburner:origLink>http://uber.la/2011/07/twitter-hack/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro-Review</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Uberla/~3/c-Wurell_d4/</link><category>community building</category><category>social media</category><category>tech reviews</category><category>tools</category><category>analytics</category><category>blog metrics</category><category>google analytics</category><category>knowing your audience</category><category>learning analytics</category><category>measuring the web</category><category>measuring your blog traffic</category><category>measuring your traffic</category><category>metrics</category><category>optimizing your blog</category><category>optimizing your content</category><category>seo</category><category>SEO traffic</category><category>web metrics</category><category>web statistics</category><category>web traffic</category><category>what are your visitors reading</category><category>wordpress analytics</category><category>writing for your audience</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">jmacofearth</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 08 Jul 2011 10:06:53 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://uber.la/?p=19023</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[
<p><span style="color: #888888;">[This is an unsolicited, un-sponsored review of Gaug.es. No promotional money or incentives were offered.]</span></p>
<p>Why would you pay for analytics when Google Analytics is free?</p>
<p>This little package <strong><a title="Gaug.es is a wonderful little analytics package" href="http://get.gaug.es/" target="_blank">gaug.es</a></strong> might just be one answer.</p>
<p><a href="http://gaug.es/"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19087" title="Gaug.es logo and tab overview" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.49.05-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 08 at 11.49.05 AM New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro Review" width="213" height="97" /></a></p>
<p>At $6 per month, I was skeptical, but kept coming back to the gaug.es dashboard during my free trial period and liking what I was seeing.</p>
<p>Here&#039;s the overview screen:</p>
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.48.49-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19088" title="gaug.es overview data screen" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.48.49-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 08 at 11.48.49 AM New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro Review" width="491" height="295" /></a></p>
<p>And the Top Pages screen can really show you a lot of information about your deep content. How many posts are actually getting traffic? Do you know what your highest, overall, traffic generating pages are? Which ones continue to get hits months or years after they&#039;ve been written? Questions like these can lead you to some healthy content strategies about what to write next.</p>
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.53.30-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19089" title="Top Pages in Gaug.es" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.53.30-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 08 at 11.53.30 AM New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro Review" width="445" height="324" /></a></p>
<p>Standard Referrers, Search, and Browsers Stats</p>
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.55.55-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19090" title="Referrers, Search and Browsers in Gaug.es" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-08-at-11.55.55-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 08 at 11.55.55 AM New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro Review" width="460" height="331" /></a></p>
<p>And the Current Visitors page. Now  has a map to pinpoint where your content is being consumed. This is again, more fun than useful, but that&#039;s part of the fascination with metrics. You can be obsessed by them, but opening GA is often a pain, and the internal WordPress plugin-type stats are often incomplete.</p>
<p>For my $6 a month, Gaug.es is a deal. And it got me thinking about the deeper content on my blog and how I can make the long tail SEO traffic work for me.</p>
<p>Go check it out for free: <a title="$6 per month for a basic account" href="http://get.gaug.es/" target="_blank">http://get.gaug.es/</a></p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> yes, I&#039;m watching you on gaug.es right now. ;-)</p>
<p>@<a title="Tweeting and measuring the traffic from the tweet" href="http://twitter.com/jmacofearth" target="_blank">jmacofearth</a><br />
Permalink: <a href="http://uber.la/2011/07/gauges/">http://uber.la/2011/07/gauges/</a></p>
<p><strong>UPDATE:</strong> And here&#039;s the pay off. I have a post that&#039;s starting to pick up some steam. It&#039;s about a <a title="The LTwitteri hack on Twitter" href="http://uber.la/2011/07/twitter-hack/">recent hack on Twitter</a>. It&#039;s fun to see the map light up with people.</p>
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-09-at-8.27.24-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19496" title="Watching a post go viral on the Live Data screen" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-09-at-8.27.24-PM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 09 at 8.27.24 PM New Simple Analytics Package, Gaug.es, Worth Paying For, the Micro Review" width="531" height="610" /></a></p>
