</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Uberla/~4/2Q4s2NFiNuE" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>Apple does not compete on price and therefore their "offer" is actually a gift card from their online app store. Dell on the other hand, competes on price and even competes with itself on price. Does any consumer think that the SPECIAL, or LIMITED TIME OFFER will not be made even better tomorrow, when Dell unveils their NEXT SALE.</description><wfw:commentRss xmlns:wfw="http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/">http://uber.la/2011/07/apple-vs-dell/feed/</wfw:commentRss><slash:comments xmlns:slash="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/">17</slash:comments><feedburner:origLink>http://uber.la/2011/07/apple-vs-dell/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>The Social Sharing Golden Rule: "And What Excites You About That?"</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Uberla/~3/ikM-G4kSLO8/</link><category>community building</category><category>connections</category><category>lifestreaming</category><category>social media</category><category>tech opinion</category><category>context</category><category>don't be a bot</category><category>learning social media</category><category>random check-ins</category><category>social sharing</category><category>Twitter Coupon</category><category>what excites you?</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">jmacofearth</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 03 Jul 2011 11:23:51 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://uber.la/?p=17231</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[
<p>We&#039;ve all done it. Sent out the link or youtube video suggestion with zero context or added value. The Tweets and Shares look like this:</p>
<ul>
<li>Funny video &#8211;  http://xyz.com</li>
<li>Check this out - http://xyz.com</li>
</ul>
<p>Those look a bit like this example of a common Twitter hack.</p>
<div><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-11-at-1.59.43-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-19902" title="a common twitter hack" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-11-at-1.59.43-PM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 11 at 1.59.43 PM The Social Sharing Golden Rule: And What Excites You About That?" width="203" height="55" /></a></div>
<p>If you don&#039;t want you sharing to be ignored. Give a bit more info.</p>
<p>And we often make random tweets or comments that are more like talking to ourselves than to an anticipatory audience of &#034;followers.&#034;</p>
<ul>
<li>You mean it could all be my LowT? Oh Pharma how you taunt me, promising the fountain of youth.</li>
</ul>
<p>But some of the worst offenders are the gowalla/4square check-ins that have no additional information.</p>
<ul>
<li>I am at McDonalds in Tempe AZ.</li>
<li>I&#039;m just ousted the Mayor of Starbucks on Cedar Street.</li>
</ul>
<p>So here&#039;s the new golden rule of social sharing. (And I am writing this to myself, also, I tweet a lot of bs, I&#039;m sure)</p>
<p>Before you hit the &#034;share,&#034; &#034;comment,&#034; or &#034;check-in&#034; button, ask yourself, &#034;<strong>And what excites you about that?</strong>&#034; and try to add that extra tidbit of content on as part of the social share. Here&#039;s an example:</p>
<ul>
<li>&#034;I am at the Whole Foods Downtown, waiting for a 15-minute chair massage on a Friday afternoon. We&#039;ve almost made it to the long weekend.&#034;</li>
</ul>
<p>There are several parts of this post that are exciting. Friday, massage, Whole Foods. It gives a little more to engage with. And yes, it&#039;s that simple. If you&#039;re gonna check in, or send a funny link, tell us why you are excited about it. Add the human part that a Twitter Coupon, Facebook Clone, Auto-Bot cannot generate. A bit of story to go along with your share.</p>
<p>If you can&#039;t articulate a quick&#8211;why this is exciting&#8211;then you might reconsider telling us all about it.</p>
<p><strong>UPDATE 7-4-11:</strong> Maybe I&#039;m overreaching on this. I know a friend in the Twitterati who recently BLOCKED my account. What? I know I gave him a poke when he would check in with the &#034;I&#039;m at&#8230;&#034; generic Gowalla&#039;s from time to time, but that was well over a year ago. I guess social media never forgets. He responded, back then, with a &#034;What&#039;s it to you?&#034; And I dutifully responded, &#034;Well, I was just curious why your &#034;I&#039;m at&#034; checkin at Starbucks was of interest. Are you trying to be the mayor?&#034;</p>
<p>And then most likely an unfollow from then on. I still had this liminary in my ATX friends list, so his tweets popped up from time to time. And even when I was genuinely interested in his topic, my @s were ignored. Okay, unfollowed and ignored, I get that. So this morning, as I was working some twitter lists and adding social media &#034;experts&#034; to my twitterstream, I came across this person&#039;s Twitter account again. And alas in some Unfollow of those not Following me I had Unfollowed him. I guess. But when I click on his &#034;FOLLOW&#034; button here&#039;s what I got.</p>
<p><a href="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-04-at-9.13.31-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-17434" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="The Twitter BLOCK message" src="http://uber.la/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Screen-shot-2011-07-04-at-9.13.31-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2011 07 04 at 9.13.31 AM The Social Sharing Golden Rule: And What Excites You About That?" width="446" height="46" /></a></p>
<p>Oh well, maybe his tweet will come up in a #hashtag search sometime, cause he&#039;s definately not interested in having me participate in his Twitter world. That&#039;s fine. Disappointing. But people can block and unfollow and tweet at who ever they like. So, to you, blockers, so sorry to miss your valuable Tweets. Not so sorry to miss your generic &#034;I&#039;m at&#034; GEO check-ins.</p>
<p>But the real sadness comes from missing out on this person&#039;s wisdom. I can&#039;t even have them in a list, they&#039;ve removed any opportunity for engagement. That&#039;s what I was working on the entire time. Even when I poked him about his Starbucks checkins. My loss, I&#039;m sure.</p>
<p><strong>Funny Note:</strong> Just as I&#039;m posting this, my now-blocked friend posted a SB check-in. At least this time he included a picture of his coffee. That&#039;s *some* context. And I&#039;ve been known to tweet &#034;I&#039;m here now, lookin at this cup of coffee&#034; posts.</p>
